class="entry-content"><div
class="entry-content-section"><h3 id="chicago-physical-therapists" class="entry-website-title">Chicago Physical Therapists</h3><div
class="entry-website-img"><div
class="entry-faux-browser"><div
class="entry-browser-menu"><div
class="dot"></div><div
class="dot"></div><div
class="dot"></div></div>
<picture>
<source
data-srcset="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=2:1,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=332&dpr=2" media="(max-width: 412px)" />
<source
data-srcset="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=495&dpr=2" media="(max-width: 575px)" />
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=650&dpr=2"
width="650"
height="403"
alt="desktop screenshot of website Chicago Physical Therapists"
/>
</picture></div></div><p
class="entry-website-detail website-detail-url">
<span
class="icon">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-link.svg" alt="chain icon" width="29" height="29" />
</span>
<a
class="force-single-line" href="https://www.chicagophysicaltherapists.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">
https://www.chicagophysicaltherapists.com/
</a></p><p
class="entry-website-detail website-detail-location">
<span
class="icon">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-pin.svg" alt="pin icon" width="30" height="30" />
</span>
<span>Chicago, Illinois, U.S.</span></p><div
class="entry-text"><p>Chicago Physical Therapists is a physical therapy clinic in Chicago that specializes in women's health, orthopedics, and sports injuries. My first impression of the website was that it was one of nurture and care, thanks to its soft pink accents.</p><p>Well-chosen quality images and concise, compellingly crafted copy aid the site's professional appeal. While I found this to make the content very easy to digest, the absence of detailed descriptions of individual services is a lost opportunity for the practice to demonstrate its knowledge and expertise.</p></div><h4>Pros and Cons</h4><div
class="entry-indented-box"><div
class="entry-website-pros">
<span
class="icon icon-sm">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-plus.svg" alt="plus sign" width="18" height="18" />
</span><div
class="entry-text"><p>Clear CTA buttons throughout the site prompt users to engage, and an online booking form makes it easy to schedule an appointment. Aside from contrast errors, WAVE detected only three instances of images missing alternative text.</p></div></div><div
class="entry-website-cons">
<span
class="icon icon-sm">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-minus.svg" alt="minus sign" width="18" height="18" />
</span><div
class="entry-text"><p>The prominent display of the logo on the home page is unnecessary as it is already displayed in the top-left corner of each page, and a more compelling hero image, such as a team photo, would make a better first impression.</p></div></div></div><h4>Desktop Review</h4><div
class="entry-website-desktop"><div
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-desktop.webp"
data-type="desktop"
class="lightbox-trigger js-lightbox-trigger"
><div
class="lightbox-thumbnail">
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=400&dpr=2"
alt="desktop screenshot of website"
width="400"
height="248"
/></div>
<img
class="lightbox-thumbnail-magnifier"
src="/assets/images/icon-magnifying.svg"
alt="magnifying glass"
width="50"
height="50"
/></div><div
class="entry-text"><p>My real-world experience of the desktop site was pleasant, with fast loading times, good contrast between text and background colors, allowing for easy reading, and appropriate images to break up the content. While it is not difficult to navigate the site, thanks to a floating top menu, I would have preferred the links to the services and conditions pages to be moved under a separate heading for easier access instead of being placed under the "About" tab.</p></div></div><h4>Mobile Review</h4><div
class="entry-website-mobile"><div
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-mobile.webp"
data-type="mobile"
class="lightbox-trigger js-lightbox-trigger"
><div
class="lightbox-thumbnail">
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-chicago-physical-therapists-2024079-mobile.webp?crop=3:5,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=375&dpr=2"
alt="mobile screenshot of website"
width="325"
height="542"
/></div>
<img
class="lightbox-thumbnail-magnifier"
src="/assets/images/icon-magnifying.svg"
alt="magnifying glass"
width="50"
height="50"
/></div><div
class="entry-text"><p>Similar to the desktop site, the mobile version features a floating hamburger menu, giving visitors easy access to the different pages of the site. While menu items with submenus are conveniently identified by a greater-than sign, I found that on mobile, submenus make the navigation experience feel lengthier than necessary.</p><p>The site's content is appropriately resized to fit smaller screens, except the practice's logo in place of a hero image, which comes across as oversized. On Google's PageSpeed Insights, the mobile site scored 48/100 for performance.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div
class="entry-container entry-container-content"><div
class="entry-content-wrapper"><div
class="entry-content"><div
class="entry-content-section"><h3 id="rise-physical-therapy" class="entry-website-title">RISE Physical Therapy</h3><div
class="entry-website-img"><div
class="entry-faux-browser"><div
class="entry-browser-menu"><div
class="dot"></div><div
class="dot"></div><div
class="dot"></div></div>
<picture>
<source
data-srcset="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=2:1,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=332&dpr=2" media="(max-width: 412px)" />
<source
data-srcset="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=495&dpr=2" media="(max-width: 575px)" />
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=650&dpr=2"
width="650"
height="403"
alt="desktop screenshot of website RISE Physical Therapy"
/>
</picture></div></div><p
class="entry-website-detail website-detail-url">
<span
class="icon">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-link.svg" alt="chain icon" width="29" height="29" />
</span>
<a
class="force-single-line" href="https://www.risephysicaltherapy.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">
https://www.risephysicaltherapy.com/
</a></p><p
class="entry-website-detail website-detail-location">
<span
class="icon">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-pin.svg" alt="pin icon" width="30" height="30" />
</span>
<span>San Diego, California, U.S.</span></p><div
class="entry-text"><p>RISE Physical Therapy, a San Diego-based practice, offers one-on-one physical therapy treatment services, which include injury-related treatments, balance training, and elite sports training. I found the colors and motif of the website's hero image make a bold, dynamic impression, which is very different from the more common muted and cool colors in this sector.</p><p>Another element that stood out to me was the choice of visuals, with many images being of the practice's staff in action instead of generic stock photos.</p></div><h4>Pros and Cons</h4><div
class="entry-indented-box"><div
class="entry-website-pros">
<span
class="icon icon-sm">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-plus.svg" alt="plus sign" width="18" height="18" />
</span><div
class="entry-text"><p>The site stands out with dynamic colors and custom visuals. Its service descriptions are agreeably concise and to the point, with individual topics being explored in more depth on the site's blog. Aside from some contrast errors, the site performed well on WAVE, which only flagged four missing form labels.</p></div></div><div
class="entry-website-cons">
<span
class="icon icon-sm">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-minus.svg" alt="minus sign" width="18" height="18" />
</span><div
class="entry-text"><p>The site is missing patient reviews, which can be crucial to prospective patients' decision-making process. While there is an online contact form, an online scheduling tool would facilitate a more streamlined booking process.</p></div></div></div><h4>Desktop Review</h4><div
class="entry-website-desktop"><div
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-2024079-desktop.webp"
data-type="desktop"
class="lightbox-trigger js-lightbox-trigger"
><div
class="lightbox-thumbnail">
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=400&dpr=2"
alt="desktop screenshot of website"
width="400"
height="248"
/></div>
<img
class="lightbox-thumbnail-magnifier"
src="/assets/images/icon-magnifying.svg"
alt="magnifying glass"
width="50"
height="50"
/></div><div
class="entry-text"><p>The home page's hero image is most effective on a larger desktop screen, visually conveying the concepts of strength and movement. While I found the text overlay to be a little too lengthy, making it look very busy, the keyword "empowering" does catch the eye, reinforcing the dynamic energy of the visual.</p><p>The remainder of the site was easy and quick to navigate, with content arranged neatly and with adequate breathing room to allow for an enjoyable user experience.</p></div></div><h4>Mobile Review</h4><div
class="entry-website-mobile"><div
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-mobile-824x16382-20240725.webp"
data-type="mobile"
class="lightbox-trigger js-lightbox-trigger"
><div
class="lightbox-thumbnail">
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-rise-physical-therapy-mobile-824x16382-20240725.webp?crop=3:5,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=375&dpr=2"
alt="mobile screenshot of website"
width="325"
height="542"
/></div>
<img
class="lightbox-thumbnail-magnifier"
src="/assets/images/icon-magnifying.svg"
alt="magnifying glass"
width="50"
height="50"
/></div><div
class="entry-text"><p>On the mobile site, the hero image on the home page is cropped and slightly obstructed by a pop-up prompt, diluting its effect. While the remaining content is suitably resized to fit smaller screens, the lack of a floating menu button left me scrolling a lot. I also found the mobile site to load slower than the desktop version, which is reflected in Google's PageSpeed Insights score of 42/100 for performance.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div
class="entry-container entry-container-content"><div
class="entry-content-wrapper"><div
class="entry-content"><div
class="entry-content-section"><h3 id="physio-solutions" class="entry-website-title">Physio Solutions</h3><div
class="entry-website-img"><div
class="entry-faux-browser"><div
class="entry-browser-menu"><div
class="dot"></div><div
class="dot"></div><div
class="dot"></div></div>
<picture>
<source
data-srcset="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-physio-solutions-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=2:1,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=332&dpr=2" media="(max-width: 412px)" />
<source
data-srcset="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-physio-solutions-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=495&dpr=2" media="(max-width: 575px)" />
<img
class="lazyload"
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-physio-solutions-2024079-desktop.webp?crop=400:248,offset-x0,offset-y0&width=650&dpr=2"
width="650"
height="403"
alt="desktop screenshot of website Physio Solutions"
/>
</picture></div></div><p
class="entry-website-detail website-detail-url">
<span
class="icon">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-link.svg" alt="chain icon" width="29" height="29" />
</span>
<a
class="force-single-line" href="https://www.physiosolutions.co.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">
https://www.physiosolutions.co.uk/
</a></p><p
class="entry-website-detail website-detail-location">
<span
class="icon">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-pin.svg" alt="pin icon" width="30" height="30" />
</span>
<span>London, England, U.K.</span></p><div
class="entry-text"><p>Physio Solutions is a London-based physiotherapy and sports injury clinic that has been providing treatment for musculoskeletal pain complaints for more than two decades. Their website was one of the more comprehensive examples I came across while researching physical therapy websites.</p><p>The site presents detailed information about the clinic and its services, along with accounts of how patients were treated and informative blog and news entries. It also features patient reviews and fee information. However, I felt its imagery was not quite up to scratch.</p></div><h4>Pros and Cons</h4><div
class="entry-indented-box"><div
class="entry-website-pros">
<span
class="icon icon-sm">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-plus.svg" alt="plus sign" width="18" height="18" />
</span><div
class="entry-text"><p>Clinic information and service descriptions are comprehensive. Contact information is easy to find, and testimonials are featured to build trust with potential patients. Aside from low contrast issues, WAVE flagged no errors, and both the desktop and mobile sites load fast.</p></div></div><div
class="entry-website-cons">
<span
class="icon icon-sm">
<img
src="/assets/images/icon-minus.svg" alt="minus sign" width="18" height="18" />
</span><div
class="entry-text"><p>The site is missing an online booking application. Some sections, such as the physiotherapy service description page, are very text-heavy and would appear less overwhelming if they incorporated more visuals. The images used on the website look unpolished.</p></div></div></div><h4>Desktop Review</h4><div
class="entry-website-desktop"><div
data-src="https://www.zarla.com/images/zarla-websiteexample-physio-solutions-2024079-desktop.webp"
data-type="desktop"
class="lightbox-trigger js-lightbox-trigger"
><div
class="lightbox-thumbnail">
<img
